<question type="stack">
  <name><text>Week 15 – Q3: Hertzian Dipole Validity and Design Correction</text></name>
  <questiontext format="html">
    <text><![CDATA[
<p>An engineer proposes to model a dipole antenna as a Hertzian dipole. The antenna parameters are:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Length: \(\ell = {@l_cm@}\) cm</li>
  <li>Current amplitude: \(I_0 = {@I_0@}\) A</li>
  <li>Operating frequency: \(f = {@f_GHz@}\) GHz</li>
  <li>Medium: free space (\(\eta_0 = 120\pi \approx 377\;\Omega\))</li>
</ul>

<h4>Part A — Validity Check</h4>

<p><b>(a)</b> Calculate the wavelength \(\lambda\).</p>
<p>\(\lambda = \) [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]] m</p>

<p><b>(b)</b> Calculate the ratio \(\ell/\lambda\).</p>
<p>\(\ell/\lambda = \) [[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]]</p>

<p><b>(c)</b> The Hertzian dipole model requires \(\ell/\lambda &lt; 0.1\). Is this model valid for the given antenna?</p>
<p>[[input:ans3]] [[validation:ans3]]</p>

<h4>Part B — Design Correction</h4>

<p>Since the model is not valid for the given length, you must propose a corrected design.</p>

<p><b>(d)</b> What is the <b>maximum antenna length</b> \(\ell_{\max}\) (in cm) for which the Hertzian dipole model would be valid at this frequency? Use the criterion \(\ell/\lambda &lt; 0.1\).</p>
<p>\(\ell_{\max} = \) [[input:ans4]] [[validation:ans4]] cm</p>

<h4>Part C — Radiation Parameters at \(\ell_{\max}\)</h4>

<p>Using \(\ell = \ell_{\max}\) from part (d), compute the antenna's radiation parameters.</p>

<p><b>(e)</b> Radiation resistance \(R_{\text{rad}} = 80\pi^2(\ell_{\max}/\lambda)^2\).</p>
<p>\(R_{\text{rad}} = \) [[input:ans5]] [[validation:ans5]] \(\Omega\)</p>

<p><b>(f)</b> Total radiated power \(P_{\text{rad}} = \frac{1}{2}I_0^2 R_{\text{rad}}\).</p>
<p>\(P_{\text{rad}} = \) [[input:ans6]] [[validation:ans6]] W</p>

<p><b>(g)</b> Directivity of a Hertzian dipole in dBi.</p>
<p>\(D = \) [[input:ans7]] [[validation:ans7]] dBi</p>
]]></text>
  </questiontext>
  <generalfeedback format="html">
    <text><![CDATA[
<h4>Worked Solution</h4>

<p><b>Given:</b> \(\ell = {@l_cm@}\) cm, \(f = {@f_GHz@}\) GHz, \(I_0 = {@I_0@}\) A.</p>

<p><b>(a)</b> \(\lambda = c/f = 3\times10^8/{@f_Hz@} = {@tans1@}\) m = {@float(tans1*100)@} cm</p>

<p><b>(b)</b> \(\ell/\lambda = {@l_cm@}/{@float(tans1*100)@} = {@tans2@}\)</p>

<p><b>(c)</b> Since \(\ell/\lambda = {@tans2@} > 0.1\), the Hertzian dipole model is <b>NOT valid</b>. The antenna is too long relative to the wavelength for the uniform-current assumption to hold.</p>

<p><b>(d)</b> Maximum valid length: \(\ell_{\max} = 0.1 \times \lambda = 0.1 \times {@float(tans1*100)@}\text{ cm} = {@tans4@}\) cm.</p>

<p><b>(e)</b> At \(\ell = \ell_{\max}\), the ratio is \(\ell/\lambda = 0.1\), so:</p>
<p>\[R_{\text{rad}} = 80\pi^2(0.1)^2 = 0.8\pi^2 \approx 7.90\;\Omega\]</p>
<p>This is always the same at the validity boundary — a key insight about how small radiation resistance is for short dipoles.</p>

<p><b>(f)</b> \(P_{\text{rad}} = \frac{1}{2} \times ({@I_0@})^2 \times 7.90 = {@tans6@}\) W</p>

<p><b>(g)</b> \(D = 1.5 = 10\log_{10}(1.5) = 1.76\) dBi. This is the same for <b>all</b> Hertzian dipoles — directivity depends only on the \(\sin^2\theta\) pattern, not on length or frequency.</p>
]]></text>
  </generalfeedback>
